		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Kiting</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:ECsoftware@hotmail.com">Bladetrack</a> | 
		            2/21/2000 5:50:59 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">REQUIREMENTS: You must be able to cast snare or move VERY fast&#8230; RECCOMENED: druid, ranger<BR>
KITING- this is a very easy concept to learn but some of you may have trouble or just want the details&#8230; Kiting begins with two entities one a PC and one an NPC. NOTE: this should be done in a wide-open space and the NPC is preferably non-trainable.  Full mana or a backpack full of arrows is usually required for each kill. DO NOT TRY THIS IN A DUNGEON&#8230; WC will do just fine or my personal favorite NK. To get the maximum amount of exp. a yellow opponent is recommended. If the opponent is red they will resist your castings more and your spells will do less damage and your arrows the same. Casting creatures are not recommended for kiting, it just DOESN&#8217;T WORK. Some creatures may move faster than others even while snared EXAMPLE: snared grizzly bears move about the same speed as you do walking backward, while pincer beetles hardly move at all. To begin the attack you must first cast snare. Then as the creature moves towards you, you must A: move backward with a bow firing at it while it tries to catch up with you. Or B: run from the creature cast a spell&#8230; run from the creature cast a spell&#8230; etc. Thus making it MUCH easier to kill things with less risk and making it possible to kill yellow creatures as well as occasional reds. This is very effective and is one of the advantages to playing a druid or a ranger.<BR>
-Bladetrack
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
